          </div>
        </div>
        <div style="display:flex; gap:26px; padding:10px 6px 0; border-top:2px dashed #DCE3EF; margin-top:0;">
          <div style="flex:1; font-size:13px; font-weight:600; color:#536084; text-align:center; line-height:1.4;">one clinic's data<br><span style="color:#8A96B0;">train + test, different patients</span></div>
          <div style="flex:1; font-size:13px; font-weight:600; color:#536084; text-align:center; line-height:1.4;">a second clinic's patients<br><span style="color:#8A96B0;">never seen, different sensors</span></div>
          <div style="flex:1; font-size:13px; font-weight:600; color:#536084; text-align:center; line-height:1.4;">trained on both<br><span style="color:#8A96B0;">tested on held-out patients</span></div>
        </div>
        <div style="font-size:13.5px; line-height:1.55; font-weight:600; color:#8A96B0; border-top:1px solid #EFF2F8; padding-top:12px; margin-top:14px;"><span style="color:#536084;">{{ ladderTitle }}</span> {{ ladderNote }}</div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div style="font-size:15px; font-weight:800; letter-spacing:1.6px; color:{{ accent }}; margin-bottom:14px;">THE HONEST TEST</div>
        <h2 style="font-size:clamp(28px,5vw,40px); line-height:1.12; font-weight:800; letter-spacing:-1px; margin:0 0 16px;">We went looking for our own failure, and found it.</h2>
        <p style="font-size:17.5px; line-height:1.6; font-weight:500; color:#3A4A66; margin:0 0 14px;">A model that looks great on one clinic's data often fails on another's, different sensors, different protocols, different patients. So we tested ours against an independent cohort collected by a different research group. It fell hard: 0.83 to 0.60.</p>
        <p style="font-size:17.5px; line-height:1.6; font-weight:500; color:#3A4A66; margin:0;">Then we fixed it the only way that holds: training across both cohorts recovers 0.86 on patients the model has never seen. That lesson is now policy, every production model trains on multiple cohorts before it ships.</p>
