  <!-- ============================================================ OUR STORY ============================================================ -->
  <sc-if value="{{ isStory }}" hint-placeholder-val="{{ false }}">
  <div style="max-width:840px; margin:0 auto; padding:70px 32px 10px; text-align:center;">
    <div style="font-size:15px; font-weight:800; letter-spacing:1.6px; color:{{ accent }}; margin-bottom:16px;">OUR STORY</div>
    <h1 style="font-size:clamp(32px,6.6vw,56px); line-height:1.06; font-weight:800; letter-spacing:-1.6px; margin:0 0 24px;">We started with a<br>simple <span style="font-style:italic; font-family:'Newsreader',serif; font-weight:600; color:{{ accent }};">purpose</span>.</h1><div><br></div><div><span style="background-color: initial; font-size: 25px;" data-dc-dragging="1"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">Cadence did not begin in a lab. It began in a house in India.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">On a trip to visit family, one of us watched what Parkinson's does to an ordinary day. His parnani, his maternal great-grandmother, was living with the disease, and the whole household moved around it. Not around her, around the disease. Around the clock.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">There was always a question hanging in the room. Had she taken her medication? Was it working yet? Was it already wearing off? Her caretakers tracked it as best they could, but the answers were never clean. Levodopa does not keep a schedule. It works, then it fades, and the fade rarely lands when you expect it. So the family guessed. They guessed at timing, guessed at doses, guessed at whether the next hour would be a good one.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">That guesswork cost them. Not just in symptoms managed poorly, but in time. Hours spent watching, worrying, recalculating. Hours that could have been spent simply being with her.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">He came home and could not put it down.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">The problem underneath the stress was math. When the last dose was taken, how the body absorbed it, how a protein-heavy meal pushed the timing, when the next off window would open. A person cannot hold all of that in their head across a day, every day, for years. But a model can.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">So we built Cadence to do the part that was breaking people: the tracking, the timing, the forecast of when symptoms would return. The goal was never to replace a caretaker's judgment. It was to hand back the mental load they were carrying alone, and with it, the hours they were losing to it.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">We measure Cadence by one thing. Not accuracy on a chart, though we hold ourselves to that. We measure it by whether it gives families more good hours together, and less energy spent bracing for the bad ones.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">That is what she deserved. That is what we are building for the next family.</p></span></div><p></p>
    
  </div>
